Fetch run logs and service logs. Canonical run-log usage is `rascal logs run <run_id>`; `rascal logs <run_id>` is a shorthand.

Usage:
  rascal logs [run_id] [flags]
  rascal logs [command]

Aliases:
  logs, tail

Examples:
rascal logs run run_abc123
rascal logs run run_abc123 --follow
rascal logs rascald --follow
rascal logs caddy-access --follow

Available Commands:
  caddy        Fetch Caddy system logs over SSH
  caddy-access Fetch Caddy access log file over SSH
  rascald      Fetch rascald system logs over SSH
  run          Fetch logs for a run

Flags:
      --follow              stream logs by polling
  -h, --help                help for logs
      --interval duration   polling interval when --follow is enabled (default 4s)
      --lines int           max log lines to fetch (default 200)
      --since duration      show logs since duration ago (best effort)

Global Flags:
      --api-token string         orchestrator API token
      --client-ssh-host string   SSH target host for API transport=ssh/auto
      --client-ssh-key string    SSH private key path for API transport=ssh/auto
      --client-ssh-port int      SSH target port for API transport=ssh/auto
      --client-ssh-user string   SSH target user for API transport=ssh/auto
      --config string            config file path (default "$HOME/.rascal/config.toml")
      --default-repo string      default repository in OWNER/REPO form
      --env-file string          env file path (fallback: ./.rascal.env if present)
      --no-color                 disable ANSI color/style output (also set by NO_COLOR)
      --output string            output format: table|json|toml (default "table")
  -q, --quiet                    reduce non-essential output
      --server-url string        orchestrator URL
      --transport string         API transport: auto|http|ssh

Use "rascal logs [command] --help" for more information about a command.
